<FONT SIZE=2>
	&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;The Adjusted EBITDA loss was $88.5&nbsp;million for the year ended December&nbsp;31, 2016, compared to an Adjusted EBITDA loss
	of
	$75.0&nbsp;million for the year ended December&nbsp;31, 2015.
</FONT>
</P>
<UL>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;MARGIN-LEFT:10.0PT;TEXT-INDENT:-10.0PT;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
<B>
<I>
<!-- COMMAND=STYLE_ADDED,"MARGIN-LEFT:10.0PT;TEXT-INDENT:-10.0PT;" -->
	Depreciation and Amortization
</I>
</B>
</FONT>
</P>
</UL>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Depreciation and amortization expense was $145.3&nbsp;million for the year ended December&nbsp;31, 2016, compared to $105.0&nbsp;million
	for the year ended December&nbsp;31, 2015. The increase was principally due to the acquisitions of Concentra on June&nbsp;1, 2015 and Physiotherapy on March&nbsp;4, 2016.
</FONT>
</P>
<UL>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;MARGIN-LEFT:10.0PT;TEXT-INDENT:-10.0PT;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
<B>
<I>
<!-- COMMAND=STYLE_ADDED,"MARGIN-LEFT:10.0PT;TEXT-INDENT:-10.0PT;" -->
	Income from Operations
</I>
</B>
</FONT>
</P>
</UL>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;For the year ended December&nbsp;31, 2016, we had income from operations of $299.8&nbsp;million, compared to $274.8&nbsp;million for the
	year ended December&nbsp;31, 2015. The increase was principally due to the acquisitions of Concentra on June&nbsp;1, 2015 and Physiotherapy on March&nbsp;4, 2016.
</FONT>
</P>
<UL>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;MARGIN-LEFT:10.0PT;TEXT-INDENT:-10.0PT;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
<B>
<I>
<!-- COMMAND=STYLE_ADDED,"MARGIN-LEFT:10.0PT;TEXT-INDENT:-10.0PT;" -->
	Loss on Early Retirement of Debt
</I>
</B>
</FONT>
</P>
</UL>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;On March&nbsp;4, 2016, we prepaid the series&nbsp;D tranche&nbsp;B term loans under the Select credit facilities, resulting in a loss on
	early retirement of debt of $0.8&nbsp;million. On September&nbsp;26, 2016, Concentra prepaid its second lien term loan under the Concentra credit facilities, resulting in a loss on early
	retirement of debt of approximately $10.9&nbsp;million. The losses on early retirement of debt consisted of a prepayment premium, unamortized debt issuance costs, and unamortized original issue
	discounts.
</FONT>
</P>
<UL>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;MARGIN-LEFT:10.0PT;TEXT-INDENT:-10.0PT;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
<B>
<I>
<!-- COMMAND=STYLE_ADDED,"MARGIN-LEFT:10.0PT;TEXT-INDENT:-10.0PT;" -->
	Equity in Earnings of Unconsolidated Subsidiaries
</I>
</B>
</FONT>
</P>
</UL>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;For the year ended December&nbsp;31, 2016, we had equity in earnings of unconsolidated subsidiaries of $19.9&nbsp;million, compared
	$16.8&nbsp;million for the year ended December&nbsp;31, 2015. The increase in our equity in earnings of unconsolidated subsidiaries resulted from increased earnings associated with several of our
	equity method investments in rehabilitation businesses.
</FONT>
</P>
<UL>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;MARGIN-LEFT:10.0PT;TEXT-INDENT:-10.0PT;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
<B>
<I>
<!-- COMMAND=STYLE_ADDED,"MARGIN-LEFT:10.0PT;TEXT-INDENT:-10.0PT;" -->
	Non-Operating Gain
</I>
</B>
</FONT>
</P>
</UL>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;We recognized a non-operating gain of $42.7&nbsp;million for the year ended December&nbsp;31, 2016, principally due to the sale of our
	contract therapy businesses for $65.0&nbsp;million, resulting in a non-operating gain of $33.9&nbsp;million.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;During
	the year ended December&nbsp;31, 2015, we recognized a non-operating gain of $29.6&nbsp;million related to the sale of an equity method investment.
</FONT>
</P>
<UL>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;MARGIN-LEFT:10.0PT;TEXT-INDENT:-10.0PT;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
<B>
<I>
<!-- COMMAND=STYLE_ADDED,"MARGIN-LEFT:10.0PT;TEXT-INDENT:-10.0PT;" -->
	Interest Expense
</I>
</B>
</FONT>
</P>
</UL>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Interest expense was $170.1&nbsp;million for the year ended December&nbsp;31, 2016, compared to $112.8&nbsp;million for the year ended
	December&nbsp;31, 2015. The increase in interest expense was principally the result of increases in our indebtedness used to finance the acquisitions of Concentra on June&nbsp;1, 2015 and
	Physiotherapy on March&nbsp;4, 2016 in addition to increases in our interest rates resulting from amendments to the Select credit facilities in the fourth quarter of 2015 and the first quarter of
	2016.
</FONT>
</P>
<UL>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;MARGIN-LEFT:10.0PT;TEXT-INDENT:-10.0PT;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
<B>
<I>
<!-- COMMAND=STYLE_ADDED,"MARGIN-LEFT:10.0PT;TEXT-INDENT:-10.0PT;" -->
	Income Taxes
</I>
</B>
</FONT>
</P>
</UL>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;We recorded income tax expense of $55.5&nbsp;million for the year ended December&nbsp;31, 2016, which represented an effective tax rate of
	30.7%. We recorded income tax expense of $72.4&nbsp;million for the year ended December&nbsp;31, 2015, which represented an effective tax rate of 34.8%.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Our
	effective tax rate for the year ended December&nbsp;31, 2016 benefited from the sale of our contract therapy businesses. Our tax basis in our contract therapy businesses exceeded
	our selling price. As a result,
</FONT>
</P>

<FONT SIZE=2>
	71
</FONT>
</P>

<A NAME="A2230888Z10-K_HTM_PAGE_DS19201_1_72">

<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY">
<FONT SIZE=2>
<A HREF="#A2230888Z10-K_HTM_BG19201A_MAIN_TOC">
	Table of Contents

<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	we
	had no tax expense from the sale. Our effective tax rate for the year ended December&nbsp;31, 2015 benefited from the resolution of uncertain tax positions.
</FONT>
</P>
<UL>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;MARGIN-LEFT:10.0PT;TEXT-INDENT:-10.0PT;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
<B>
<I>
<!-- COMMAND=STYLE_ADDED,"MARGIN-LEFT:10.0PT;TEXT-INDENT:-10.0PT;" -->
	Net Income Attributable to Non-Controlling Interests
</I>
</B>
</FONT>
</P>
</UL>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Net income attributable to non-controlling interests was $9.9&nbsp;million for the year ended December&nbsp;31, 2016, compared to
	$5.3&nbsp;million for the year ended December&nbsp;31, 2015. The increase is principally due to the acquisition of Concentra, offset in part by the minority interest owners' share of losses from
	new specialty hospitals.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;MARGIN-LEFT:10.0PT;TEXT-INDENT:-10.0PT;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
<B>
<!-- COMMAND=STYLE_ADDED,"MARGIN-LEFT:10.0PT;TEXT-INDENT:-10.0PT;" -->
	Year Ended December&nbsp;31, 2015 Compared to Year Ended December&nbsp;31, 2014
</B>
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;In the following, we discuss our results of operations related to net operating revenues, operating expenses, Adjusted EBITDA, depreciation and
	amortization, income from operations, loss on early retirement of debt, equity in earnings of unconsolidated subsidiaries, non-operating gain (loss), interest expense, income taxes, and
	non-controlling interest, which, in each case, are the same for Holdings and Select.
</FONT>
</P>
<UL>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;MARGIN-LEFT:10.0PT;TEXT-INDENT:-10.0PT;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
<B>
<I>
<!-- COMMAND=STYLE_ADDED,"MARGIN-LEFT:10.0PT;TEXT-INDENT:-10.0PT;" -->
	Net Operating Revenues
</I>
</B>
</FONT>
</P>
</UL>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Our net operating revenues increased by $677.7&nbsp;million to $3,742.7&nbsp;million for the year ended December&nbsp;31, 2015, compared
	to $3,065.0&nbsp;million for the year ended December&nbsp;31, 2014.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY">
<FONT SIZE=2>
<I>
	&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Specialty Hospitals.
</I>
</FONT>
<FONT SIZE=2>
	&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Our specialty hospitals segment net operating revenues increased 4.5% to
	$2,346.8&nbsp;million for the year ended December&nbsp;31, 2015, compared to $2,244.9&nbsp;million for the year ended December&nbsp;31, 2014. The segment experienced growth in its patient
	services revenues which resulted from increases in patient days and an increase in our net revenues per patient day. Patient days increased to 1,373,780&nbsp;days for the year ended
	December&nbsp;31, 2015, compared to 1,340,506&nbsp;days for the year ended December&nbsp;31, 2014. The average net revenue per patient day increased to $1,569 for the year ended
	December&nbsp;31, 2015, compared to $1,546 for the year ended December&nbsp;31, 2014, due to increases in both our Medicare and non-Medicare net revenue per patient day. The occupancy percentage
	was 72% for the year ended December&nbsp;31, 2015, compared to 70% for the year ended December&nbsp;31, 2014.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY">
<FONT SIZE=2>
<I>
	&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Outpatient Rehabilitation.
</I>
</FONT>
<FONT SIZE=2>
	&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Our outpatient rehabilitation segment net operating revenues decreased to $810.0&nbsp;million for the year
	ended
	December&nbsp;31, 2015, compared to $819.4&nbsp;million for the year ended December&nbsp;31, 2014. This decrease resulted from a reduction in net operating revenues at our contract therapy
	business, offset in part by increases in net operating revenues at our outpatient rehabilitation clinics. The net operating revenues generated by our outpatient rehabilitation clinics for the year
	ended December&nbsp;31, 2015 increased 5.3%, compared to the year ended December&nbsp;31, 2014. This growth was principally due to a 5.0% increase in visits to 5,218,532 at our owned clinics. Net
	revenue per visit in our owned outpatient rehabilitation clinics was $103 for both the years ended December&nbsp;31, 2015 and 2014. The net operating revenues generated by our contract therapy
	business for the year ended December&nbsp;31, 2015 decreased $42.3&nbsp;million, compared to the year ended December&nbsp;31, 2014, which principally resulted from contract terminations.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY">
<FONT SIZE=2>
<I>
	&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Concentra Segment.
</I>
</FONT>
<FONT SIZE=2>
	&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;For the period from June&nbsp;1, 2015 to December&nbsp;31, 2015, net operating revenues were $585.2&nbsp;million,
	visits
	were 4,436,977 in the medical centers, and net revenue per visit was $114.
</FONT>
</P>
<UL>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;MARGIN-LEFT:10.0PT;TEXT-INDENT:-10.0PT;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
<B>
<I>
<!-- COMMAND=STYLE_ADDED,"MARGIN-LEFT:10.0PT;TEXT-INDENT:-10.0PT;" -->
	Operating Expenses
</I>
</B>
</FONT>
</P>
</UL>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Our operating expenses include our cost of services, general and administrative expense and bad debt expense. Our operating expenses increased
	by $650.8&nbsp;million to $3,363.0&nbsp;million, or 89.9% of net operating revenues, for the year ended December&nbsp;31, 2015, compared to $2,712.2&nbsp;million, or 88.5% of net operating
	revenues, for the year ended December&nbsp;31, 2014, principally due to the acquisition of Concentra on June&nbsp;1,
</FONT>
</P>
<P ALIGN="CENTER" STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	72
</FONT>
</P>

<P STYLE='FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;PAGE-BREAK-BEFORE:ALWAYS'>

<!-- ZEQ.=5,SEQ=74,EFW="2230888",CP="SELECT MEDICAL HOLDINGS CORPORAT",DN="1",CHK=782664,FOLIO='72',FILE='DISK133:[17ZAA1.17ZAA19201]DS19201A.;12',USER='JTAYLORA',CD='23-FEB-2017;10:54' -->
<A NAME="A2230888Z10-K_HTM_PAGE_DS19201_1_73">
</A>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY">
<FONT SIZE=2>
<A HREF="#A2230888Z10-K_HTM_BG19201A_MAIN_TOC">
	Table of Contents
</A>
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	2015.
	Our cost of services, a major component of which is labor expense, was $3,211.5&nbsp;million, or 85.8% of net operating revenues, for the year ended December&nbsp;31, 2015, compared to
	$2,582.3&nbsp;million, or 84.2% of net operating revenues, for the year ended December&nbsp;31, 2014. Approximately half of the increase in cost of services as a percent of net operating revenues
	resulted from the addition of Concentra which operated with a higher relative cost of services percentage to net operating revenues during the year ended December&nbsp;31, 2015, as compared to the
	relative cost of services percentage to net operating revenues experienced overall by Select in the year ended December&nbsp;31, 2015. The other half of the increase occurred in our specialty
	hospitals segment and resulted principally from non-recurring increases in labor costs associated with several training initiatives, including training to prepare for the adoption of patient criteria
	and incremental costs resulting from a higher staff turnover rate for the year ended December&nbsp;31, 2015, as compared to 2014. Facility rent expense, a component of cost of services, was
	$169.8&nbsp;million for the year ended December&nbsp;31, 2015 compared to $128.7&nbsp;million for the year ended December&nbsp;31, 2014. General and administrative expenses were
	$92.1&nbsp;million for the year ended December&nbsp;31, 2015, compared to $85.2&nbsp;million for the year ended December&nbsp;31, 2014 and were 2.5% and 2.8% of net operating revenues for the
	years ended December&nbsp;31, 2015 and 2014, respectively. The increase in general and administrative expenses resulted primarily from Concentra acquisition costs of $4.7&nbsp;million. Our bad
	debt expense was $59.4&nbsp;million, or 1.6% of net operating revenues, for the year ended December&nbsp;31, 2015, compared to $44.6&nbsp;million, or 1.5% of net operating revenues, for the year
	ended December&nbsp;31, 2014. This is principally a result of higher relative bad debt expense in our specialty hospitals segment, compared to the year ended December&nbsp;31, 2014, and at
	Concentra.
</FONT>
</P>
<UL>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;MARGIN-LEFT:10.0PT;TEXT-INDENT:-10.0PT;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
<B>
<I>
<!-- COMMAND=STYLE_ADDED,"MARGIN-LEFT:10.0PT;TEXT-INDENT:-10.0PT;" -->
	Adjusted EBITDA
</I>
</B>
</FONT>
</P>
</UL>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY">
<FONT SIZE=2>
<I>
	&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Specialty Hospitals.
</I>
</FONT>
<FONT SIZE=2>
	&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Adjusted EBITDA for our specialty hospitals decreased to $327.6&nbsp;million for the year ended December&nbsp;31,
	2015,
	compared to $341.8&nbsp;million for the year ended December&nbsp;31, 2014. Our Adjusted EBITDA margin for the segment was 14.0% for the year ended December&nbsp;31, 2015, compared to 15.2% for
	the year ended December&nbsp;31, 2014. The decline in Adjusted EBITDA and Adjusted EBITDA margin for our specialty hospitals segment was attributable to increases in our cost of services and bad
	debt expense as discussed above under "
</FONT>
<FONT SIZE=2>
<I>
	Operating Expenses
</I>
</FONT>
<FONT SIZE=2>
	."
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY">
<FONT SIZE=2>
<I>
	&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Outpatient Rehabilitation.
</I>
</FONT>
<FONT SIZE=2>
	&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Our Adjusted EBITDA for our outpatient rehabilitation segment increased 0.7% to $98.2&nbsp;million for the
	year ended
	December&nbsp;31, 2015, compared to $97.6&nbsp;million for the year
	ended December&nbsp;31, 2014. Our Adjusted EBITDA margin for the outpatient rehabilitation segment was 12.1% for the year ended December&nbsp;31, 2015 compared to 11.9% for the year ended
	December&nbsp;31, 2014. The Adjusted EBITDA in our outpatient rehabilitation clinics increased by $7.4&nbsp;million for the year ended December&nbsp;31, 2015, compared to the year ended
	December&nbsp;31, 2014. The increase in Adjusted EBITDA for our outpatient rehabilitation clinics was principally the result of increases in net operating revenues as discussed above under
	"
</FONT>
<FONT SIZE=2>
<I>
	Net Operating Revenues
</I>
</FONT>
<FONT SIZE=2>
	." Our Adjusted EBITDA margin for our outpatient rehabilitation clinics was 13.8% for the year ended December&nbsp;31, 2015,
	compared to 13.3% for the year ended December&nbsp;31, 2014. Our contract therapy business experienced a decrease in Adjusted EBITDA of $6.8&nbsp;million, compared to the year ended
	December&nbsp;31, 2014, which principally resulted from contract terminations as discussed above under "
</FONT>
<FONT SIZE=2>
<I>
	Net Operating Revenues
</I>
</FONT>
<FONT SIZE=2>
	."
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY">
<FONT SIZE=2>
<I>
	&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Concentra Segment.
</I>
</FONT>
<FONT SIZE=2>
	&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;For the period June&nbsp;1, 2015 to December&nbsp;31, 2015, Adjusted EBITDA was $48.3&nbsp;million and the Adjusted
	EBITDA
	margin for the segment was 8.3%.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY">
<FONT SIZE=2>
<I>
	&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Other.
</I>
</FONT>
<FONT SIZE=2>
	&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;The Adjusted EBITDA loss was $75.0&nbsp;million for the year ended December&nbsp;31, 2015, compared to an Adjusted EBITDA loss of
	$75.5&nbsp;million for the year ended December&nbsp;31, 2014.
</FONT>
</P>
<P ALIGN="CENTER" STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	73

<FONT SIZE=2>
	&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Depreciation and amortization expense was $105.0&nbsp;million, including $33.6&nbsp;million in our Concentra segment, for the year ended
	December&nbsp;31, 2015, compared to $68.4&nbsp;million for the year ended December&nbsp;31, 2014.
</FONT>
</P>
<UL>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;MARGIN-LEFT:10.0PT;TEXT-INDENT:-10.0PT;">

<!-- COMMAND=STYLE_ADDED,"MARGIN-LEFT:10.0PT;TEXT-INDENT:-10.0PT;" -->
	Income from Operations
</I>
</B>

</P>
</UL>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;For the year ended December&nbsp;31, 2015, we had income from operations of $274.8&nbsp;million, compared to $284.5&nbsp;million for the
	year ended December&nbsp;31, 2014. The decrease in our income from operations resulted principally from increases in operating expenses at our specialty hospitals segment, as discussed above under
	"
</FONT>
<FONT SIZE=2>
<I>
	Operating Expenses
</I>
</FONT>
<FONT SIZE=2>
	," and was offset in part by the incremental contribution from of our Concentra segment since June&nbsp;1, 2015.
</FONT>
</P>
<UL>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;MARGIN-LEFT:10.0PT;TEXT-INDENT:-10.0PT;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
<B>
<I>
<!-- COMMAND=STYLE_ADDED,"MARGIN-LEFT:10.0PT;TEXT-INDENT:-10.0PT;" -->
	Loss on Early Retirement of Debt
</I>
</B>
</FONT>
</P>
</UL>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;On March&nbsp;4, 2014, we amended the Select term loans. During the year ended December&nbsp;31, 2014, we recognized a loss of
	$2.3&nbsp;million for unamortized debt issuance costs, unamortized original issue discount and certain fees incurred related to the Select term loan modifications.
</FONT>
</P>
<UL>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;MARGIN-LEFT:10.0PT;TEXT-INDENT:-10.0PT;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
<B>
<I>
<!-- COMMAND=STYLE_ADDED,"MARGIN-LEFT:10.0PT;TEXT-INDENT:-10.0PT;" -->
	Equity in Earnings of Unconsolidated Subsidiaries
</I>
</B>
</FONT>
</P>
</UL>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;For the year ended December&nbsp;31, 2015, we had equity in earnings of unconsolidated subsidiaries of $16.8&nbsp;million, compared to
	$7.0&nbsp;million for the year ended December&nbsp;31, 2014. The increase in our equity in earnings of unconsolidated subsidiaries resulted from increased earnings associated with several of our
	inpatient rehabilitation joint ventures and improved financial results at the start-up companies in which we own a non-controlling interest.
</FONT>
</P>
<UL>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;MARGIN-LEFT:10.0PT;TEXT-INDENT:-10.0PT;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
<B>
<I>
<!-- COMMAND=STYLE_ADDED,"MARGIN-LEFT:10.0PT;TEXT-INDENT:-10.0PT;" -->
	Non-operating gain
</I>
</B>
</FONT>
</P>
</UL>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;For the year ended December&nbsp;31, 2015, we had a gain on the sale of an equity investment of $29.6&nbsp;million. The equity investment
	was a start-up company investment in which we owned a non-controlling interest.
</FONT>
</P>
<UL>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;MARGIN-LEFT:10.0PT;TEXT-INDENT:-10.0PT;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
<B>
<I>
<!-- COMMAND=STYLE_ADDED,"MARGIN-LEFT:10.0PT;TEXT-INDENT:-10.0PT;" -->
	Interest Expense
</I>
</B>
</FONT>
</P>
</UL>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Interest expense was $112.8&nbsp;million for the year ended December&nbsp;31, 2015, compared to $85.4&nbsp;million for the year ended
	December&nbsp;31, 2014. The increase in interest expense was principally due to increases in our indebtedness to finance the Concentra acquisition.
</FONT>
</P>
<UL>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;MARGIN-LEFT:10.0PT;TEXT-INDENT:-10.0PT;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
<B>
<I>
<!-- COMMAND=STYLE_ADDED,"MARGIN-LEFT:10.0PT;TEXT-INDENT:-10.0PT;" -->
	Income Taxes
</I>
</B>
</FONT>
</P>
</UL>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;We recorded income tax expense of $72.4&nbsp;million for the year ended December&nbsp;31, 2015, which represented an effective tax rate of
	34.8%. We recorded income tax expense of $75.6&nbsp;million for the year ended December&nbsp;31, 2014, which represented an effective tax rate of 37.1%. The decrease in the effective tax rate has
	resulted principally from the resolution of uncertain tax positions.
</FONT>
</P>
<UL>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;MARGIN-LEFT:10.0PT;TEXT-INDENT:-10.0PT;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
<B>
<I>
<!-- COMMAND=STYLE_ADDED,"MARGIN-LEFT:10.0PT;TEXT-INDENT:-10.0PT;" -->
	Net Income Attributable to Non-Controlling Interests
</I>
</B>
</FONT>
</P>
</UL>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Net income attributable to non-controlling interests was $5.3&nbsp;million for the year ended December&nbsp;31, 2015, compared to
	$7.5&nbsp;million for the year ended December&nbsp;31, 2014. These amounts represent the minority owner's share of income and losses in consolidated entities, such as Concentra, in which our
	ownership is less than 100.0%. The decrease was principally caused by net losses in our Concentra segment for the year ended December&nbsp;31, 2015, which offset positive net income from other
	consolidated entities.
</FONT>
</P>

<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Operating
	activities provided $346.6&nbsp;million of cash flows for the year ended December&nbsp;31, 2016. The increase in operating cash flows for the year ended December&nbsp;31,
	2016 compared to the year ended December&nbsp;31, 2015 is principally due to cash flows provided from Concentra which was acquired on June&nbsp;1, 2015 and cash distributions we received from
	unconsolidated investments in which we are minority owners.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Operating
	activities provided $208.4&nbsp;million of cash flows for the year ended December&nbsp;31, 2015. The increase in operating cash flows for the year ended December&nbsp;31,
	2015 compared to the year ended December&nbsp;31, 2014 is principally due to the addition of Concentra.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Our
	days sales outstanding were 51&nbsp;days at December&nbsp;31, 2016, 53&nbsp;days at December&nbsp;31, 2015, and 53&nbsp;days at December&nbsp;31, 2014. Our days sales
	outstanding will fluctuate based upon variability in our collection cycles. Our days sales outstanding at December&nbsp;31, 2016, 2015 and 2014 all fall within our normal range for accounts
	receivable turnover.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Investing
	activities used $554.3&nbsp;million, $1,211.8&nbsp;million and $101.1&nbsp;million of cash flow for the years ended December&nbsp;31, 2016, 2015 and 2014, respectively.
	For the year ended December&nbsp;31, 2016, the principal use of cash was $406.3&nbsp;million for the Physiotherapy acquisition and $161.6&nbsp;million for purchases of property and equipment,
	offset in part by the sale of assets and businesses of $80.5&nbsp;million. For the year ended December&nbsp;31, 2015, the principal use of cash was $1,047.2&nbsp;million for the Concentra
	acquisition and $182.6&nbsp;million for purchases of property and equipment, offset in part by the proceeds from the sale of an equity investment. For the year ended December&nbsp;31, 2014, the
	principal use of cash was $95.2&nbsp;million for purchases of property and equipment.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Financing
	activities provided $292.3&nbsp;million of cash flow for the year ended December&nbsp;31, 2016. The principal source of cash was the issuance of $625.0&nbsp;million
	series&nbsp;F tranche&nbsp;B term loans under the Select credit facilities, resulting in net proceeds of $600.1&nbsp;million, offset by $215.7&nbsp;million of cash used to repay the
	series&nbsp;D tranche&nbsp;B term loans under the Select credit facilities and $80.0&nbsp;million of net repayments under the Select and Concentra revolving facilities.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Financing
	activities provided $1,014.4&nbsp;million of cash flows for the year ended December&nbsp;31, 2015. Cash was principally provided from $235.0&nbsp;million of net
	borrowings under the Select revolving facility, $5.0&nbsp;million of net borrowings under the Concentra revolving facility, $646.9&nbsp;million borrowed under the Concentra credit facilities, and
	$217.1&nbsp;million attributable to non-consolidating interests in Concentra Group Holdings. The principal uses of cash for financing activities were $26.9&nbsp;million for mandatory prepayment of
	term loans under the Select credit facilities, $23.3&nbsp;million for Concentra's debt issuance costs, $13.6&nbsp;million for common stock repurchases and $13.1&nbsp;million for dividend
	payments to common stockholders.
</FONT>
</P>

<FONT SIZE=2>

<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY">
<FONT SIZE=2>
<A HREF="#A2230888Z10-K_HTM_BG19201A_MAIN_TOC">
	Table of Contents
</A>
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Financing activities used $70.5&nbsp;million of cash flows for the year ended December&nbsp;31, 2014. Cash was principally used by a $34.0&nbsp;million
	mandatory prepayment of term loans under the Select credit facilities, $10.0&nbsp;million for purchases of non-controlling interests, and $184.1&nbsp;million used to repurchase shares of common
	stock and pay dividends to common stockholders. This was offset in part by $40.0&nbsp;million in net borrowings under the Select revolving facility and $111.7&nbsp;million from the issuance of
	additional 6.375% senior notes.
</FONT>
</P>
<UL>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;MARGIN-LEFT:10.0PT;TEXT-INDENT:-10.0PT;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
<B>
<I>
<!-- COMMAND=STYLE_ADDED,"MARGIN-LEFT:10.0PT;TEXT-INDENT:-10.0PT;" -->
	Capital Resources
</I>
</B>
</FONT>
</P>
</UL>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY">
<FONT SIZE=2>
<I>
	&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Working capital.
</I>
</FONT>
<FONT SIZE=2>
	&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;We had net working capital of $236.4&nbsp;million at December&nbsp;31, 2016 compared to net working capital of
	$19.9&nbsp;million at December&nbsp;31, 2015. The increase in net working capital is primarily due to the early retirement of series&nbsp;D tranche&nbsp;B term loans, which were classified as
	a current liability at December&nbsp;31, 2015, and an increase in cash during the year ended December&nbsp;31, 2016.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY">
<FONT SIZE=2>
<I>
	&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Select credit facilities.
</I>
</FONT>
<FONT SIZE=2>
	&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;On March&nbsp;2, 2016, Select made a mandatory term loan principal prepayment of $10.2&nbsp;million as a
	result of the
	annual excess cash flow provision contained in the Select credit facilities.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;On
	March&nbsp;4, 2016, Select amended the Select credit facilities in order to, among other things: (i)&nbsp;have the lenders named therein make available an aggregate of
	$625.0&nbsp;million series&nbsp;F tranche&nbsp;B term loans, (ii)&nbsp;extend the financial covenants through March&nbsp;3, 2021, (iii)&nbsp;add a 1.00% prepayment premium for prepayments
	made with new term loans on or prior to March&nbsp;4, 2017 if such new term loans have a lower yield than the series&nbsp;F tranche&nbsp;B term loans, (iv)&nbsp;increase the interest rate
	payable on the series&nbsp;E tranche&nbsp;B term loans from Adjusted LIBO plus 4.00% (subject to an Adjusted LIBO Rate floor of 1.00%), or Alternate Base Rate plus 3.00%, to Adjusted LIBO plus
	5.00% (subject to an Adjusted LIBO rate floor of 1.00%), or Alternate Base Rate plus 4.00%; and (v)&nbsp;made certain other technical amendments to the Select credit facilities. The series&nbsp;F
	tranche&nbsp;B term loans bear interest at a rate per annum equal to the Adjusted LIBO Rate (as defined in the Select credit facilities, subject to an Adjusted LIBO Rate floor of 1.00%) plus 5.00%
	for Eurodollar Loans or the Alternate Base Rate (as defined in the Select credit facilities) plus 4.00% for Alternate Base Rate Loans (as defined in the Select credit facilities). Select is required
	to make principal payments on the series&nbsp;F tranche&nbsp;B term loans in quarterly installments on the last day of each of March, June, September and December, beginning June&nbsp;30, 2016,
	in amounts equal to 0.25% of the aggregate principal amount of the series&nbsp;F tranche&nbsp;B term loans outstanding as of the date of the credit extension amendment. The balance of the
	series&nbsp;F tranche&nbsp;B term loans is payable on March&nbsp;3, 2021. Except as specifically set forth in the credit extension amendment, the terms and conditions of the series&nbsp;F
	tranche&nbsp;B term loans are identical to the terms of the outstanding series&nbsp;E tranche&nbsp;B term loans under the Select credit facilities and the other loan documents to which Select is
	party.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Select
	used the proceeds of the series&nbsp;F tranche&nbsp;B term loans to (i)&nbsp;refinance in full the series&nbsp;D tranche&nbsp;B term loans due December&nbsp;20, 2016,
	(ii)&nbsp;consummate the acquisition of Physiotherapy, and (iii)&nbsp;pay fees and expenses incurred in connection with the acquisition of Physiotherapy, the refinancing, and the Select credit
	extension amendment.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;At
	December&nbsp;31, 2016, Select had outstanding borrowings under the Select credit facilities of $1,147.8&nbsp;million of Select term loans (excluding unamortized discounts and
	debt issuance costs of $25.6&nbsp;million) and borrowings of $220.0&nbsp;million (excluding letters of credit) under the Select revolving facility. At December&nbsp;31, 2016, Select had
	$190.3&nbsp;million of availability under the Select revolving facility after giving effect to $39.7&nbsp;million of outstanding letters of credit.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;The
	Select credit facilities require Select to maintain certain leverage ratios (as defined in the Select credit facilities). For the four consecutive fiscal quarters ended
	December&nbsp;31, 2016, Select was required to maintain its leverage ratio (its ratio of total indebtedness to consolidated EBITDA) at less than 5.75 to 1.00. Select's leverage ratio was 5.40 to
	1.00 as of December&nbsp;31, 2016. Additionally, the Select credit facilities will require a prepayment of borrowings of 50% of excess cash flow for fiscal year 2016, which will result in a
	prepayment of approximately $33.2&nbsp;million based on excess cash flow for the year ended
</FONT>
</P>
<P ALIGN="CENTER" STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	76
</FONT>
</P>

</A>

</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	December&nbsp;31,
	2016. The Company expects to have the borrowing capacity and intends to use borrowings under the Select revolving facility to make the required prepayment during the quarter ended
	March&nbsp;31, 2017.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY">
<FONT SIZE=2>
<I>
	&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Concentra credit facilities.
</I>
</FONT>
<FONT SIZE=2>
	&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Select and Holdings are not parties to the Concentra credit facilities and are not obligors with respect
	to Concentra's
	debt under such agreements. While this debt is non-recourse to Select, it is included in Select's consolidated financial statements.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;On
	September&nbsp;26, 2016, Concentra entered into an amendment to the Concentra credit agreement dated June&nbsp;1, 2015. The Concentra credit agreement initially provided for
	$500.0&nbsp;million in first lien credit facilities composed of a $450.0&nbsp;million, seven-year Concentra first lien term loans and a $50.0&nbsp;million Concentra revolving facility. The
	amendment provided an additional $200.0&nbsp;million of first lien term loans due June&nbsp;1, 2022, the proceeds of which were used to prepay in full the Concentra's second lien term loan due
	June&nbsp;1, 2023; and also amended certain restrictive covenants to give Concentra greater operational flexibility.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;The
	Concentra first lien term loan continues to bear interest at a rate equal to Adjusted LIBO (as defined in the Concentra credit agreement) plus 3.00% (subject to an Adjusted LIBO
	floor of 1.00%), or Alternate Base Rate (as defined in the Concentra credit agreement) plus 2.00% (subject to an Alternate Base Rate floor of 2.00%). The Concentra first lien term loan amortizes in
	equal quarterly installments of $1.6&nbsp;million through March&nbsp;31, 2022, with the remaining unamortized aggregate principal due on at maturity on June&nbsp;1, 2022.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;At
	December&nbsp;31, 2016, Concentra had outstanding borrowings under the Concentra credit facilities of $642.2&nbsp;million (excluding unamortized discounts and debt issuance costs
	of $15.9&nbsp;million) of term loans. Concentra did not have any borrowings under the Concentra revolving facility. At December&nbsp;31, 2016, Concentra had $43.4&nbsp;million of availability
	under its revolving facility after giving effect to $6.6&nbsp;million of outstanding letters of credit.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;The
	Concentra credit facilities will require a prepayment of borrowings of 25% of excess cash flow for fiscal year 2016, which will result in a prepayment of approximately
	$23.1&nbsp;million based on excess cash flow for the year ended December&nbsp;31, 2016. Concentra expects to have the borrowing capacity and intends to use borrowings under the Concentra revolving
	facility and cash on hand to make the required prepayment during the quarter ended March&nbsp;31, 2017.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY">
<FONT SIZE=2>
<I>
	&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Stock Repurchase Program.
</I>
</FONT>
<FONT SIZE=2>
	&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Holdings' board of directors has authorized a common stock repurchase program to repurchase up to
	$500.0&nbsp;million
	worth of shares of its common stock. The program has been extended until December&nbsp;31, 2017, and will remain in effect until then, unless further extended or earlier terminated by the board of
	directors. Stock repurchases under this program may be made in the open market or through privately negotiated transactions, and at times and in such amounts as Holdings deems appropriate. Holdings
	funds this program with cash on hand and borrowings under the Select revolving facility. Holdings did not repurchase shares during the year ended December&nbsp;31, 2016. Since the inception of the
	program through December&nbsp;31, 2016, Holdings has repurchased 35,924,128 shares at a cost of approximately $314.7&nbsp;million, or $8.76 per share, which includes transaction costs.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY">
<FONT SIZE=2>
<I>
	&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Liquidity.
</I>
</FONT>
<FONT SIZE=2>
	&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;We believe our internally generated cash flows and borrowing capacity under the Select and Concentra credit facilities will
	be sufficient
	to finance operations over the next twelve months. We may from time to time seek to retire or purchase our outstanding debt through cash purchases and/or exchanges for equity securities, in open
	market purchases, privately negotiated transactions, tender offers or otherwise. Such repurchases or exchanges, if any, may be funded from operating cash flows or other sources and will depend on
	prevailing market conditions, our liquidity requirements, contractual restrictions and other factors. The amounts involved may be material. We also may refinance our credit facilities depending upon
	prevailing market conditions.
</FONT>
</P>
<P ALIGN="CENTER" STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	77
</FONT>

<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY">
<FONT SIZE=2>
<I>
	&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Use of Capital Resources.
</I>
</FONT>
<FONT SIZE=2>
	&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;We may from time to time pursue opportunities to develop new joint venture relationships with significant
	health systems
	and other healthcare providers, and from time to time we may also develop new inpatient rehabilitation hospitals and medical centers. We also intend to open new outpatient rehabilitation clinics in
	local areas that we currently serve where we can benefit from existing referral relationships and brand awareness to produce incremental growth. In addition to our development activities, we may grow
	through opportunistic acquisitions.
</FONT>
</P>

<!-- ZEQ.=3,SEQ=80,EFW="2230888",CP="SELECT MEDICAL HOLDINGS CORPORAT",DN="1",CHK=658477,FOLIO='78',FILE='DISK133:[17ZAA1.17ZAA19201]DU19201A.;25',USER='JTAYLORA',CD='23-FEB-2017;10:54' -->
<A NAME="A2230888Z10-K_HTM_PAGE_DU19201_1_79">
</A>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY">
<FONT SIZE=2>
<A HREF="#A2230888Z10-K_HTM_BG19201A_MAIN_TOC">
	Table of Contents
</A>
</FONT>
</P>
<DIV STYLE="PADDING:0PT;POSITION:RELATIVE;TEXT-ALIGN:LEFT;MARGIN-LEFT:10%;">
<DL COMPACT>
<DT STYLE='FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;MARGIN-BOTTOM:-11PT;'>
<FONT SIZE=2>
	(7)
</FONT>
</DT>
<DD STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	The
	interest obligation for the Concentra credit facilities was calculated using the average interest rate at December&nbsp;31, 2016 of 4.0% for the Concentra
	first lien term loans. The weighted average interest rate for Concentra's other debt obligations was 7.7%.
</FONT>
</DD>
</DL>
</DIV>
<UL>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;MARGIN-LEFT:10.0PT;TEXT-INDENT:-10.0PT;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
<B>
<I>
<!-- COMMAND=STYLE_ADDED,"MARGIN-LEFT:10.0PT;TEXT-INDENT:-10.0PT;" -->
	Concentra Class&nbsp;A Put Right
</I>
</B>
</FONT>
</P>
</UL>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;In connection with the acquisition of Concentra, WCAS and the other members of Concentra Group Holdings will have the Put Right with respect to
	their equity interests in Concentra Group Holdings. If the Put Right is exercised by WCAS, Select will be obligated to purchase up to 33
<SUP>
	1
</SUP>
	/
<SMALL>
	3
</SMALL>
	% of the equity interests of Concentra Group
	Holdings that WCAS purchased on June&nbsp;1, 2015, at a purchase price based on a valuation of Concentra Group Holdings performed by an investment bank to be mutually agreed upon between Select and
	WCAS. The valuation will be based on certain precedent transactions using multiples of EBITDA and capped at an agreed upon multiple of EBITDA. Select has the right to elect to pay the purchase price
	in cash or in shares of Holdings' common stock. WCAS may first exercise its Put Right after June&nbsp;1, 2018, and then may exercise its Put Right again annually during each fiscal year thereafter.
	If WCAS exercises its Put Right, the other members of Concentra Group Holdings may elect to sell to Select, on the same terms as WCAS, a percentage of their equity interests of Concentra Group
	Holdings that such member purchased on June&nbsp;1, 2015, up to but not exceeding the percentage of its initial equity interests that WCAS has determined to sell to Select in the exercise of its Put
	Right plus the same percentage of the equity interests that such member had the right to sell but declined to sell in connection with any previous put exercise by WCAS.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;In
	addition, WCAS and the other members of Concentra Group Holdings have a Put Right with respect to their equity interest in Concentra Group Holdings that may only be exercised in the
	event Holdings or Select experiences a change of control that has not been previously approved by WCAS and which results in change in the senior management of Select. If an SEM COC Put Right is
	exercised by WCAS, Select will be obligated to purchase all (but not less than all) of the equity interests in Concentra Group Holdings of WCAS and each other member of Concentra Group Holdings, at a
	purchase price based on a valuation of Concentra Group Holdings performed by an investment bank to be mutually agreed upon between Select and WCAS, which valuation will be based on certain precedent
	transactions using multiples of EBITDA and capped at an agreed upon multiple of EBITDA.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Furthermore,
	Select has a call right (the "Call Right"), whereby each other member of Concentra Group Holdings will be obligated to sell all (but not less than all) of their equity
	interests in Concentra Group Holdings to Select at a purchase price based on a valuation of Concentra Group Holdings performed by an investment bank to be mutually agreed upon between Select and WCAS.
	The valuation will be based on certain precedent transactions using multiples of EBITDA and capped at an agreed upon multiple of EBITDA. Select may first exercise the Call Right after June&nbsp;1,
	2020. We exclude the approximate amount that we may be required to pay to purchase these equity interests in Concentra Group Holdings from the contractual obligations table above because of the
	uncertainty as to: (i)&nbsp;whether or not the Put Right, if exercisable, or the Call Right, will actually be exercised; (ii)&nbsp;the dollar amounts that would be paid if the Put Right or Call
	Right is exercised; and (iii)&nbsp;the timing and form of consideration of any such payments.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;MARGIN-LEFT:10.0PT;TEXT-INDENT:-10.0PT;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
<B>
<!-- COMMAND=STYLE_ADDED,"MARGIN-LEFT:10.0PT;TEXT-INDENT:-10.0PT;" -->
	Effects of Inflation and Changing Prices
</B>
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;We derive a substantial portion of our revenues from the Medicare program. We have been, and could be in the future, affected by the continuing
	efforts of governmental and private third-party payors to contain healthcare costs by limiting or reducing reimbursement payments.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Additionally,
	reimbursement payments under governmental and private third-party payor programs may not increase to sufficiently cover increasing costs. Medicare reimbursement in our
	specialty hospitals is subject to fixed payments under the Medicare prospective payment systems. In accordance with
</FONT>
</P>
<P ALIGN="CENTER" STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	79
</FONT>
</P>
<HR NOSHADE>
<P STYLE='FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;PAGE-BREAK-BEFORE:ALWAYS'>
</P>
<!-- ZEQ.=4,SEQ=81,EFW="2230888",CP="SELECT MEDICAL HOLDINGS CORPORAT",DN="1",CHK=407855,FOLIO='79',FILE='DISK133:[17ZAA1.17ZAA19201]DU19201A.;25',USER='JTAYLORA',CD='23-FEB-2017;10:54' -->
<A NAME="A2230888Z10-K_HTM_PAGE_DU19201_1_80">
</A>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY">
<FONT SIZE=2>
<A HREF="#A2230888Z10-K_HTM_BG19201A_MAIN_TOC">
	Table of Contents
</A>
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	Medicare
	laws, CMS makes annual adjustments to Medicare payments under what is commonly known as a "market basket update." Generally, these rates are adjusted for inflation. However, these adjustments
	may not reflect the actual increase in the costs of providing healthcare services and may be reduced by CMS for other adjustments.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;The
	healthcare industry is labor intensive and the Company's largest expenses are labor related costs. Wage and other expenses increase during periods of inflation and when labor
	shortages occur in the marketplace. There can be no guarantee we will not experience increases in the cost of labor, as the need for clinical healthcare professionals is expected to grow. In addition,
	suppliers pass along rising costs to us in the form of higher prices. We have little or no ability to pass on these increased costs associated with providing services due to federal laws that
	establish fixed reimbursement rates.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;MARGIN-LEFT:10.0PT;TEXT-INDENT:-10.0PT;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
<B>
<!-- COMMAND=STYLE_ADDED,"MARGIN-LEFT:10.0PT;TEXT-INDENT:-10.0PT;" -->
	Recent Accounting Pronouncements
</B>
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;In October 2016, the Financial Accounting Standards Board (the "FASB") issued Accounting Standards Update ("ASU") 2016-16, Income
</FONT>
<FONT SIZE=2>
<I>
	Taxes (Topic 740), Intra-Entity
	Transfers of Assets Other Than Inventory.
</I>
</FONT>
<FONT SIZE=2>
	Current GAAP prohibits the recognition of current and deferred income taxes
	for an intra-entity asset transfer until the asset has been sold to an outside party. The ASU requires an entity to recognize the income tax consequences of an intra-entity transfer of an asset other
	than inventory when the transfer occurs. The standard will be effective for fiscal years beginning after
	December&nbsp;15, 2017. The Company is currently evaluating the standard to determine the impact it will have on its consolidated financial statements.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;In
	August 2016, the FASB issued ASU 2016-15
</FONT>
<FONT SIZE=2>
<I>
	, Statement of Cash Flows (Topic 230), Classification of Certain Cash Receipts and Cash
	Payments,
</I>
</FONT>
<FONT SIZE=2>
	which addresses the diversity in practice in how certain cash receipts and cash payments are presented and classified in the statement of cash flows. The standard
	will be effective for fiscal years beginning after December&nbsp;15, 2017. The Company does not anticipate changes to current accounting policies or the need to retrospectively adjust previously
	presented consolidated financial statements as a result of the adoption of the guidance in the new standard.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;In
	February 2016, the FASB issued ASU 2016-02,
</FONT>
<FONT SIZE=2>
<I>
	Leases
</I>
</FONT>
<FONT SIZE=2>
	. This ASU includes a lessee accounting model that recognizes two types of leases;
	finance and operating. This ASU requires that a lessee recognize on the balance sheet assets and liabilities for all leases with lease terms of more than twelve months. Lessees will need to recognize
	almost all leases on the balance sheet as a right-of-use asset and a lease liability. For income statement purposes, the FASB retained the dual model, requiring leases to be classified as either
	operating or finance. The recognition, measurement, and presentation of expenses and cash flows arising from a lease by a lessee will depend on its classification as a finance or operating lease. For
	short-term leases of twelve months or less, lessees are permitted to make an accounting election by class of underlying asset not to recognize right-of-use assets or lease liabilities. If the
	alternative is elected, lease expense would be recognized generally on the straight-line basis over the respective lease term.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;The
	amendments in ASU 2016-02 will take effect for public companies for fiscal years beginning after December&nbsp;15, 2018, including interim periods within those fiscal years.
	Earlier application is permitted as of the beginning of an interim or annual reporting period. A modified retrospective approach is required for leases that exist or are entered into after the
	beginning of the earliest comparative period in the financial statements.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Upon
	adoption, the Company will recognize significant assets and liabilities on the consolidated balance sheets as a result of the operating lease obligations of the Company. Operating
	lease expense will still be recognized as rent expense on a straight-line basis over the respective lease term in the consolidated statements of operations and comprehensive income.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;In
	November 2015, the FASB issued ASU No.&nbsp;2015-17,
</FONT>
<FONT SIZE=2>
<I>
	Balance Sheet Classification of Deferred Taxes
</I>
</FONT>
<FONT SIZE=2>
	, which changes the presentation
	of deferred income taxes. The intent is to simplify the presentation of
</FONT>
</P>
<P ALIGN="CENTER" STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	80
</FONT>
</P>
<HR NOSHADE>
<P STYLE='FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;PAGE-BREAK-BEFORE:ALWAYS'>
</P>
<!-- ZEQ.=5,SEQ=82,EFW="2230888",CP="SELECT MEDICAL HOLDINGS CORPORAT",DN="1",CHK=711955,FOLIO='80',FILE='DISK133:[17ZAA1.17ZAA19201]DU19201A.;25',USER='JTAYLORA',CD='23-FEB-2017;10:54' -->
<A NAME="A2230888Z10-K_HTM_PAGE_DU19201_1_81">
</A>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY">
<FONT SIZE=2>
<A HREF="#A2230888Z10-K_HTM_BG19201A_MAIN_TOC">
	Table of Contents
</A>
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	deferred
	income taxes through the requirement that deferred tax liabilities and assets be classified as noncurrent in a classified statement of financial position. The revised guidance is effective
	for annual fiscal periods beginning after December&nbsp;15, 2016. Early adoption is permitted. The Company will adopt the guidance in this ASU in the first quarter of 2017. Upon adoption, deferred
	tax assets and liabilities will no longer be classified as current and will instead be classified as noncurrent on the consolidated balance sheets. The Company will still be required to offset
	deferred tax assets and liabilities for each taxpaying entity within a tax jurisdiction.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;In
	May 2014, March 2016, April 2016, and December 2016, the FASB issued ASU 2014-09,
</FONT>
<FONT SIZE=2>
<I>
	Revenue from Contracts with Customers
</I>
</FONT>
<FONT SIZE=2>
	, ASU 2016-08,
</FONT>
<FONT SIZE=2>
<I>
	Revenue from Contracts with Customers,
	Principal versus Agent Considerations
</I>
</FONT>
<FONT SIZE=2>
	, ASU 2016-10,
</FONT>
<FONT SIZE=2>
<I>
	Revenue from Contracts with
	Customers, Identifying Performance Obligations and Licensing
</I>
</FONT>
<FONT SIZE=2>
	, ASU 2016-12,
</FONT>
<FONT SIZE=2>
<I>
	Revenue from Contracts with Customers, Narrow Scope Improvements and
	Practical Expedients
</I>
</FONT>
<FONT SIZE=2>
	, and ASU 2016-20,
</FONT>
<FONT SIZE=2>
<I>
	Technical Corrections and Improvements to Topic 606, Revenue from Contracts with Customer
</I>
</FONT>
<FONT SIZE=2>
	(collectively "the standards"), respectively, which supersede most of the current revenue recognition requirements. The core principle of the new guidance is that an entity should recognize revenue to
	depict the transfer of promised goods or services to customers in an amount that reflects the consideration to which the entity expects to be entitled in exchange for those goods or services. New
	disclosures about the nature, amount, timing and uncertainty of revenue and cash flows arising from contracts with customers are also required. The original standards were effective for fiscal years
	beginning after December&nbsp;15, 2016; however, in July 2015, the FASB approved a one-year deferral of these standards, with a new effective date for fiscal years beginning after
	December&nbsp;15, 2017. The standards require the selection of a retrospective or cumulative effect transition method. The Company will adopt the guidance beginning January&nbsp;1, 2018, using a
	retrospective transition method.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;The
	Company anticipates the most significant change will be how the estimate for the allowance for doubtful accounts will be recognized under the new standards. Under the current
	standards, the Company's estimate for amounts not expected to be collected based on our historical experience have been recorded to bad debt expense. Under the new standards, the Company's estimate
	for amounts not expected to be collected based on historical experience will be recognized as a reduction to revenue. Subsequent changes in estimates of collectability due to a change in the financial
	status of a payor, for example a bankruptcy, will continue to be recognized as bad debt expense. Amounts previously written off to the allowance for bad debts as a result of our inability to collect
	payment will be recognized as a reduction to revenue under the new standard.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;MARGIN-LEFT:10.0PT;TEXT-INDENT:-10.0PT;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
<B>
<!-- COMMAND=STYLE_ADDED,"MARGIN-LEFT:10.0PT;TEXT-INDENT:-10.0PT;" -->
	Recently Adopted Accounting Pronouncements
</B>
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;In March 2016, the FASB issued ASU 2016-09,
</FONT>
<FONT SIZE=2>
<I>
	Compensation-Stock Compensation
</I>
</FONT>
<FONT SIZE=2>
	, which simplifies
	various aspects of accounting for share-based payments. The areas for simplification involve several aspects of the accounting for share-based payment transactions, including the income tax
	consequences and classification on the statements of cash flows. During the fourth quarter of 2016, the Company adopted and applied the standard on a prospective basis beginning January&nbsp;1,
	2016. The Company has elected to recognize the effect of forfeitures in compensation cost when they occur. There was no retrospective impact to the consolidated financial statements, including the
	consolidated statements of cash flows, as a result of the adoption of this standard.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;In
	April and August 2015, the FASB issued ASU 2015-03 and ASU 2015-15, each titled
</FONT>
<FONT SIZE=2>
<I>
	Interest-Imputation of Interest
</I>
</FONT>
<FONT SIZE=2>
	, to simplify the
	presentation of debt issuance costs. The standard requires debt issuance costs be presented in the balance sheet as a direct deduction from the carrying value of the debt liability. The FASB also
	confirmed that debt issuance costs related to line-of-credit arrangements will continue to be recognized as an asset and amortized over the term of the arrangement. The Company adopted the standard at
	the beginning of the first quarter of 2016. The balance sheet as of December&nbsp;31, 2015 was retrospectively conformed to reflect the adoption of the standard and approximately
</FONT>
</P>
<P ALIGN="CENTER" STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	81
</FONT>
</P>

	of unamortized debt issuance costs were reclassified to be a direct reduction of debt, rather than a component of other assets.

<EFX_MARKET_RISK>
<A NAME="FIS_MARKET_RISK"></A>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY">
<FONT SIZE=2>
<A NAME="A2230888Z10-K_HTM_DU19201_ITEM_7A__QUANTITATIVE_AND_QUAL__ITE02650">
</A>
<A NAME="A2230888Z10-K_HTM_TOC_DU19201_1">
</A>
</FONT>
<FONT SIZE=2>
<B>
	Item&nbsp;7A.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
</B>
</FONT>
<FONT SIZE=2>
<B>
<I>
	Quantitative and Qualitative Disclosures About Market Risk.
<BR>
</I>
</B>
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;We are subject to interest rate risk in connection with our variable rate long-term indebtedness. Our principal interest rate exposure relates
	to the loans outstanding under the Select credit facilities and Concentra credit facilities.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;As
	of December&nbsp;31, 2016, Select had $1,147.8&nbsp;million (excluding unamortized discounts and debt issuance discounts) in term loans outstanding under the Select credit
	facilities and $220.0&nbsp;million in revolving borrowings outstanding under the Select credit facilities, which bear interest at variable rates.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;As
	of December&nbsp;31, 2016, Concentra had outstanding borrowings under the Concentra credit facilities of $642.2&nbsp;million (excluding unamortized discounts and debt issuance
	costs) of term loans, which bear interest at variable rates. Concentra did not have any outstanding revolving borrowings. Certain of Select's and Concentra's outstanding borrowings that bear interest
	at variable rates may be effectively fixed based upon then current interest rates if the Adjusted LIBO Rate does not exceed the applicable Adjusted LIBO Rate floors for such
	borrowings:
</FONT>
</P>
<UL>
<DL COMPACT>
<DT STYLE='FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;MARGIN-BOTTOM:-11PT;'>
<FONT SIZE=2>
	&#149;
</FONT>
</DT>
<DD STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	Select's aggregate $527.4&nbsp;million in series&nbsp;E tranche&nbsp;B term loans are subject to an Adjusted LIBO Rate floor of 1.00%.
	Therefore, if the Adjusted LIBO Rate does not exceed 1.00%, Select's interest rate on this indebtedness is effectively fixed at 6.00%.
</FONT>
<FONT SIZE=2>
<BR>
<BR>
</FONT>
</DD>
<DT STYLE='FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;MARGIN-BOTTOM:-11PT;'>
<FONT SIZE=2>
	&#149;
</FONT>
</DT>
<DD STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	Select's aggregate $620.3&nbsp;million in series&nbsp;F tranche&nbsp;B term loans are subject to an Adjusted LIBO Rate floor of 1.00%.
	Therefore, if the Adjusted LIBO Rate does not exceed 1.00%, Select's interest rate on this indebtedness is effectively fixed at 6.00%.
</FONT>
<FONT SIZE=2>
<BR>
<BR>
</FONT>
</DD>
<DT STYLE='FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;MARGIN-BOTTOM:-11PT;'>
<FONT SIZE=2>
	&#149;
</FONT>
</DT>
<DD STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	The $642.2&nbsp;million Concentra first lien term loans are subject to an Adjusted LIBO Rate floor of 1.00%. Therefore, if the Adjusted LIBO
	Rate does not exceed 1.00%, Concentra's interest rate on this indebtedness is effectively fixed at 4.00%
</FONT>
</DD>
</DL>
</UL>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;However,
	the Select and Concentra revolving borrowings are not subject to an Adjusted LIBO Rate floor.
</FONT>
</P>

<EFX_CONTROL_AND_PROCEDURES>
<A NAME="FIS_CONTROL_AND_PROCEDURES"></A>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY">
<FONT SIZE=2>
<A NAME="A2230888Z10-K_HTM_DU19201_ITEM_9A__CONTROLS_AND_PROCEDURES_">
</A>
<A NAME="A2230888Z10-K_HTM_TOC_DU19201_4">
</A>
</FONT>
<FONT SIZE=2>
<B>
	Item&nbsp;9A.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
</B>
</FONT>
<FONT SIZE=2>
<B>
<I>
	Controls and Procedures.
<BR>
</I>
</B>
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;MARGIN-LEFT:10.0PT;TEXT-INDENT:-10.0PT;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
<B>
<!-- COMMAND=STYLE_ADDED,"MARGIN-LEFT:10.0PT;TEXT-INDENT:-10.0PT;" -->
	Evaluation of Disclosure Controls and Procedures
</B>
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;We carried out an evaluation, under the supervision and with the participation of our principal executive officer and principal financial
	officer, of the effectiveness of the design and operation of our disclosure controls and procedures (as defined in Rule&nbsp;13a-15(e) of the Securities Exchange Act of 1934) as of the end of the
	period covered in this report. Based on this evaluation, our principal executive officer and principal financial officer concluded that our disclosure controls and procedures, including the
	accumulation and communication of disclosure to our principal executive officer and principal financial officer as appropriate to allow timely decisions regarding disclosure, are effective as of
	December&nbsp;31, 2016 to provide reasonable assurance that material information required to be included in our periodic SEC reports is recorded, processed, summarized, and reported within the time
	periods specified in the relevant SEC rules and forms.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;MARGIN-LEFT:10.0PT;TEXT-INDENT:-10.0PT;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
<B>
<!-- COMMAND=STYLE_ADDED,"MARGIN-LEFT:10.0PT;TEXT-INDENT:-10.0PT;" -->
	Physiotherapy Acquisition
</B>
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;On March&nbsp;4, 2016, we consummated the acquisition of Physiotherapy. SEC guidance permits management to omit an assessment of an acquired
	business' internal control over financial reporting from management's assessment of internal control over financial reporting for a period not to exceed one year from the date of the acquisition, and
	at this time Select is omitting an assessment of Physiotherapy's internal controls over financial reporting.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;MARGIN-LEFT:10.0PT;TEXT-INDENT:-10.0PT;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
<B>
<!-- COMMAND=STYLE_ADDED,"MARGIN-LEFT:10.0PT;TEXT-INDENT:-10.0PT;" -->
	Changes in Internal Control over Financial Reporting
</B>
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;There was no change in our internal control over financial reporting (as defined in Rule&nbsp;13a-15(f) of the Securities Exchange Act of
	1934) identified in connection with the evaluation required by Rule&nbsp;13a-15(d) of the Securities Exchange Act of 1934 that occurred during the fourth quarter of the year ended
	December&nbsp;31, 2016 that has materially affected, or is reasonably likely to materially affect, our internal control over financial reporting.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;MARGIN-LEFT:10.0PT;TEXT-INDENT:-10.0PT;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
<B>
<!-- COMMAND=STYLE_ADDED,"MARGIN-LEFT:10.0PT;TEXT-INDENT:-10.0PT;" -->
	Inherent Limitations on Effectiveness of Controls
</B>
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;It should be noted that any system of controls, however well designed and operated, can provide only reasonable, and not absolute, assurance
	that the objectives of the system will be met. In addition, the design of any control system is based in part upon certain assumptions about the likelihood of future events. Because of these and other
	inherent limitations of control systems, there is only reasonable assurance that our controls will succeed in achieving their goals under all potential future conditions.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;MARGIN-LEFT:10.0PT;TEXT-INDENT:-10.0PT;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
<B>
<!-- COMMAND=STYLE_ADDED,"MARGIN-LEFT:10.0PT;TEXT-INDENT:-10.0PT;" -->
	Management's Report on Internal Control over Financial Reporting
</B>
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Management is responsible for establishing and maintaining an adequate system of internal control over our financial reporting. In order to
	evaluate the effectiveness of internal control over financial reporting, as required by Section&nbsp;404 of the Sarbanes-Oxley Act, management has conducted an assessment, including testing, using
	the criteria of "Internal Control&#151;Integrated Framework (2013)" issued by the Committee of Sponsoring Organizations of the Treadway Commission, or "COSO," as of December&nbsp;31, 2016.
	Our system of internal control over financial reporting is designed to provide reasonable assurance regarding the reliability of financial reporting and the preparation and fair presentation of
	financial statements for external purposes in accordance with U.S. generally accepted accounting principles.
</FONT>
</P>
<P ALIGN="CENTER" STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	83
</FONT>
</P>

<P STYLE='FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;PAGE-BREAK-BEFORE:ALWAYS'>

<FONT SIZE=2>
<A HREF="#A2230888Z10-K_HTM_BG19201A_MAIN_TOC">
	Table of Contents
</A>
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;The
	operations and related assets of Physiotherapy are excluded from management's assessment of internal control over financial reporting as of December&nbsp;31, 2016 because it was
	acquired by the Company in a purchase business combination during 2016. Physiotherapy's acquired assets (excluding its goodwill and intangible assets) represented less than 2% of our total assets and
	approximate revenues represented less than 6% of our total revenues of the related consolidated financial statements as of and for the year ended December&nbsp;31, 2016.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Because
	of its inherent limitations, internal control over financial reporting may not prevent or detect misstatements. Also, projections of any evaluation of effectiveness of internal
	control over financial reporting to future periods are subject to the risk that controls may become inadequate because of changes in conditions, or that the degree of compliance with the policies or
	procedures may deteriorate.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY">
<FONT SIZE=2>
	&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Management
	assessed the effectiveness of the Company's internal control over financial reporting, excluding the recently completed Physiotherapy acquisition as of December&nbsp;31,
	2016. This assessment was based on criteria for effective internal control over financial reporting described in "Internal Control&#151;Integrated Framework (2013)" issued by COSO. Based on
	this assessment, management concludes that, as of December&nbsp;31, 2016, internal control over financial reporting was effective to provide reasonable assurance regarding the reliability of
	financial reporting and the preparation of financial statements in accordance with U.S. generally accepted accounting principles. The effectiveness of the Company's internal control over financial
	reporting as of December&nbsp;31, 2016 has been audited by PricewaterhouseCoopers&nbsp;LLP, an independent registered public accounting firm as stated in their report which appears herein.
</FONT>
</P>

	under these headings is incorporated herein by reference. Information regarding the executive officers of the Company is included in this Annual Report on Form&nbsp;10-K under Item&nbsp;1 of

	have adopted a written code of business conduct and ethics, known as our code of conduct, which applies to all of our directors, officers, and employees, as well as a code of ethics
	applicable to our senior financial officers, including our chief executive officer, our chief financial officer and our chief accounting officer. Our code of conduct and code of ethics for senior
	financial officers are available on our Internet website, www.selectmedicalholdings.com. Our code of conduct and code of ethics for senior financial officers may also be obtained by contacting
	investor relations at (717)&nbsp;972-1100. Any amendments to our code of conduct or code of ethics for senior financial officers or waivers from the provisions of the codes for our chief executive
	officer, our chief financial officer and our chief accounting officer will be disclosed on our Internet website promptly following the date of such amendment or waiver.

	The following financial information from the Registrant's Annual Report on Form&nbsp;10-K for the year ended December&nbsp;31, 2016 formatted in XBRL (eXtensible Business Reporting Language): (i)&nbsp;Consolidated Statements of Operations and
	Comprehensive Income for the years ended December&nbsp;31, 2016, 2015 and 2014 (ii)&nbsp;Consolidated Balance Sheets as of December&nbsp;31, 2016 and 2015, (iii)&nbsp;Consolidated Statements of Cash Flows for the years ended December&nbsp;31, 2016,
	2015 and 2014, (iv)&nbsp;Consolidated Statements of Changes in Equity and Income for the years ended December&nbsp;31, 2016, 2015 and 2014 and (v)&nbsp;Notes to Consolidated Financial Statements.
